<dl id="n56288c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56288c">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56288c"> 288(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Manu (adam) <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56288c"><li>FW 525.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n56288c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n56288c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56288c">MS BL 47487-221v</ms> </li><li>JJA 62:412 <a name="rAd11y" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rAd11y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd11.htm#n56288c">Draft: III&sect;3A.11</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Beckett&apos;s notes: &lsquo;Manu, first man. Vischnu as fish.&rsquo;]</font>In the morning light of a new world day, <mark>Manu, the first man</mark>, asked the Allgod Vishnu to reveal the secret of the interplay between the world nights and days. In the shape of a fish, Vishnu &hellip; had rescued the pious man, chosen to be the Adam of a new world era, so that he would not drown in the great flood. <small> Heinrich Zimmer, <a name="HZMI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HZMI"><cite title="source">Maya der indische Mythos</cite></a> (1936) 48</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
